#import "../../lib.typ": chapter

#chapter(12, "The secret conversations of not-so-silent upperclasswomen")[
  "Uta-sama, thank you SO SO MUCH." Mikoto clasped her hand.

  "Uhm- thank you too!" Mona continued, expressing her gratitude to her friend.

  "You two really are... Especially Mikoto! You were the one orchestrating this
  entire event." Uta pointed her finger at Mikoto, "I'm going home."

  "No, don't! I'm sorry, okay? Please, go with us to one more club, alright?
  Mona wanted to check out the clubs with you too! Right, Mona?"

  "Uhm, yes, I do!"

  With this, Mona finally picked Mikoto's side. Though, it was not like she had
  a choice, since saying no would mean the _did_ mind visiting clubs with Uta's
  presence, which could not be further from the truth.

  "Well, it's not like I have a choice, wasn't it?"

  "Thank you so much, Uta!" Mikoto repeated her motions from earlier, with Mona
  now joining in as well.

  Mikoto, after everything that ensued, came to the window to feel the breeze
  for a brief moment. She leaned towards the window, letting her ponytail cutely
  swayed in the wind.

  "But, Koto-senpai is truly a nice person."

  "Much more than YOU."

  Uta replied to Mikoto with a personal attack, which Mikoto was not able to
  resist. She would then also come to the window, pulling her phone out to kill
  time while Mikoto was resting with the cool wind.

  Meanwhile, Mona stood there by the clubroom door, trying to recharge her
  social battery, which had reached a new low today.

  Noticing her friend standing still, Mikoto broke the silence,

  "Hey, Mona! Come here if you are tired too!"

  "Heh- I’m okay." Mona reluctantly shook her head, "Just staying here is fine."

  "Don’t be like that. The chilling spring breeze is really relaxing."

  Mikoto then let out a soft breath. She seemed to be enjoying herself.

  Mona now had no choice other than to reluctantly came to the window frames.

  _"It really feels great here..."_

  Meanwhile, in the clubroom that they were just left from...

  "Do you seriously think they will come here again?" A voice broke the silence,
  sourcing from the seat right next to Koto.

  "Don’t be rude like that, it’s not their faults for being uninterested in our
  hobbies, you know?"

  "I'm just being realistic here. You should just chase them away or something,
  what a waste of time."

  "You don’t get it, do you? These girls are so cute, I just want to keep them
  here forever! It's a shame that they left so early..." Koto grinned, in a
  slightly creepy tone.

  "Okay, keep glazing younger girls like that and you'll be the main character
  of the monthly pedo exposed drama."

  "I have not stooped to that level! Anyways, did we have a thing or two about
  using slangs in the clubroom? You are ruining the vibes for everyone else."
  Koto spoke in a strict yet mischievous tone, "Anyone felt disturbed by Ako,
  please raise your hand!"

  The other club members raised their hands half-heartedly. They just wanted to
  poke fun at the two bickering girls in their club and nothing more.

  "It's just the natural process of language evolution like it has been for
  thousands of years, y'know. Stop being so old-fashioned."

  "Ako, why don't you end your sentences with skibidi toilet if you like changes
  that much? It's the language of the next generation after us, right?"

  Koto sighed. Ever since her friend picked up a conversation with her, she
  could not focus on her reading.

  The girl who just had a playful banter with her was Tsukishima Ako, the vice
  president of the Classical Literature club, who was also a long-time childhood
  friend of Koto.

  Unlike Koto who liked to see the flustered expressions of her juniors, Ako's
  sole interest was just Koto. She loved her friend to the point of studying
  hard just to go to the same high school as her, joining the Classical
  Literature club while not knowing jack about the subject just to end up in the
  same club with her, and, always sitting next to her in the clubroom.

  Koto seemed to not notice the strangeness of her friend, however. She would be
  freaked out if she did, anyway.

  Though, to be fair, Ako had helped Koto quite a lot throughout their shared
  childhood. Koto had been not quite good with handling people, so it was lucky
  for her to have Ako handle all the hard work. After everything ended up being
  done and well, Koto would always be in awe of her friend, while still clueless
  about Ako's real intention.

  "Anyway, was that the Narumi Mona girl that I've been hearing about recently?
  She was much more shy than I expected from the little sister of Narumi Sena."
  Koto questioned.

  "She's just like you back then."

  "Can't deny that." Koto laughed. "If I were me exactly one year earlier, I
  would never be the club president like today. And that special-grade
  extraordinary performance scholarship too."

  Koto started to reminiscence about the past. Back when the club was at risk of
  shutting down due to conflicts between the seniors and the club advisor, and
  how she had to taken the role of club president while she was still a
  freshman. Thanks to Ako's help, she started to be able to get over her fears
  of socializing, and become a great club president idolized by her peers.

  When the two finally stopped their conversation, the three girls outside the
  room were finally ready for the next club visit.

  "Information Technology Club"

  "Woah- this one sounds more interesting."

  "It's literally the name of a subject, Mikoto."

  "Ah, right, we had that in the entrance exam, too... So this should be a club
  about computers..." Mikoto pondered, "Mona! You were somewhat nerdy, so maybe
  computers might be your forte!"

  "My dad has one, but all that I've touched it for was just my IT
  assignments..." Mona reluctantly replied in a seemingly apologetic tone.

  "Oh- you don't have to feel bad about it, Mona, anyway, we're going in now."
  Mikoto knocked the clubroom door, "Excuse me, we are here to check the club!"

  The door opened, revealed a male student shorter than the three girls,

  "Wel...come to the Information Technology Club!" He said in an
  almost-unhearable tone.
]
